## What This Guide Covers {.unnumbered}

You’ll find guidance on:

-   **[Text mining / Natural Language Processing (NLP)]{.plum-600}**\
    (e.g., word frequency, sentiment analysis, topic modeling)

-   **[Thematic and content analysis]{.plum-600}**\
    (e.g., dictionary-based coding, thematic coding frameworks)

-   **[Narrative analysis @qualBPT do we need?]{.plum-600}**\
    (Optional: e.g., structural analysis, language style matching)

-   **[Visualizing and reporting qualitative data]{.plum-600}**\
    (e.g., word clouds, bar charts, heatmaps, joint displays for
    mixed-methods)

These methods can be applied to text from: Word documents (.docx), PDFs
(.pdf), Zoom transcripts (.docx or .txt), open-ended survey responses
(.xlsx or .csv), and more.

In many applied settings, qualitative methods (and especially
mixed-methods) are described in vague terms. Reports may mention "themes
emerging" or "triangulating findings," but rarely explain the actual
process used to get there. This vagueness makes it hard to replicate or
assess qualitative findings and limits their credibility.




